{"ts":"2026-06-27T12:20:35.907Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Consolidating Data Integration**\n\nI'm considering how best to integrate AI Operations mock data within `lib/api-auth.ts`. I believe extending the existing file or adding a dedicated section at the end is the most effective approach to maintain data integrity and simple imports, without unnecessary duplication.\n\n\n**Clarifying Scope & Fields**\n\nI've re-read the task requirements to ensure I grasp the MVP scope. My current focus is defining the AI Operation record fields derived from the specified filters. I'm now structuring the fields for an `ApiAiOperation` model including `id`, `name`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `status`, `health`, `agent_type`, `governance_status`, and `owner`.\n\n\n**Aligning Mock Data Models**\n\nI'm now comparing the fields I've structured for `ApiAiOperation` with the existing `AgentOperation` interface in `lib/mock-data-model.ts`. There are some differences. I need to consolidate the data models, considering potential overlaps and making sure I address the existing properties for consistent, usable mock data within `lib/api-auth.ts`. I also added `description` and `lastUpdated` to my list.\n\n\n**Refining Data Structures**\n\nI'm now refining the `ApiAiOperation` structure. I've added `client_name` to map with other models, and updated the types of `status`, `health`, `agent_type`, and `governance_status` to represent the range of expected values. I am also planning to seed the mock data with 4-5 high-fidelity records, similar to how `API_MOCK_PROJECTS` works, and ensuring that the mock data has a similar structure.\n\n\n**Planning Implementation Steps**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementation planning. My current strategy is to append the `ApiAiOperation` interface, mock seed data, and helper functions directly to `lib/api-auth.ts`. This seems logical, given that file's existing structure and export functionalities. I've begun outlining my internal design plan, specifically addressing page narratives, visual metaphors, layout strategies, and interaction methods for a smooth and efficient implementation. I'm carefully reviewing the task requirements again to verify I am not touching unnecessary files or UI elements, in order to create MVP APIs.\n\n\n**Defining API Endpoint Focus**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on defining the `/api/v1/ai-operations` endpoints. I've confirmed these APIs cater specifically to portal/admin AI operations records, distinct from live GFF AI tool execution. The endpoints will include GET list/by id, POST create, PATCH update, and DELETE/archive operations, with access controlled via RBAC for admins and clients. Importantly, this is backend only, and I'll ensure no UI changes are necessary and that the APIs are secure and strictly typed, meeting the core requirements.\n\n\n**Confirming Test Implementation**\n\nI've decided to create a dedicated test script, `scripts/test-ai-operations-apis.js`, modeled after existing test scripts for CRUD APIs. I'll focus on comprehensive RBAC enforcement checks, considering all user roles and thorough filtering. I'll definitely integrate the test run output for validation purposes as well. This will ensure full compliance and confidence in the new API's functionality.\n\n\n**Detailing Data Structures**\n\nI'm now detailing data structures for mock and production data. I'm focusing on creating a comprehensive, robust test script to confirm full API functionality, filter handling, and role management for all CRUD operations. This ensures compliance with all requests. I've also begun writing down the internal design plan.\n\nI have decided to write an internal design plan first.\n1. **Narrative/Context**: This is an enterprise-grade sovereign AI operations telemetry database and management layer. It tracks deployed autonomous workflows, LLM validators, and multi-agent alignment runners across security enclaves (SGX, AMD SEV-SNP, AWS Nitro). Each operation is bound to a client and project, tracking its health, governance status, agent type, and owner.\n2. **Visual Metaphor (For internal representation)**: Hardware security enclave isolated state machine tracking multi-agent operational telemetry logs.\n3. **Layout/Structure Strategy (Files/Routes)**:\n   - `app/api/v1/ai-operations/route.ts`:\n     - GET: List all operations. Enforces RBAC. Admins get all records. Clients get only operations belonging to their projects.\n     - GET: Get a single operation by ID\n     - POST: Create a new operation (admins only). Includes validation and sanitization.\n     - PATCH: Update an existing operation (admins only). Handles partial updates.\n     - DELETE/Archive: Delete or Archive an operation (admins only). Use soft delete (add `archived_at` timestamp).\n   - Mock Data (`lib/api-auth.ts`): Seeded with a few realistic records, with variations in status, health, and governance status.\n4.  **Error Handling**: Consistent error responses across all endpoints (e.g., 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized, 403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found, 500 Internal Server Error).\n5.  **Data Validation/Sanitization**:\n    -   Server-side validation of all input data (using Zod or similar).\n    -   Sanitization to prevent injection attacks.\n    -   Data type validation, required fields, and format checks.\n6.  **Authentication/Authorization**: RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) using JWTs.\n    -   Admins have full access.\n    -   Clients can only access their own project operations.\n7.  **Testing**:\n    -   Comprehensive unit tests for each API endpoint.\n    -   Integration tests with different user roles (admins, clients).\n    -   Mock data to simulate various scenarios.\n    -   Use `scripts/test-ai-operations-apis.js` to run.\n8.  **Performance Considerations**:\n    -   Database indexing for efficient querying.\n    -   Pagination for large datasets.\n    -   Caching (if necessary).\n9.  **Deployment**:\n    -   Follow standard deployment process.\n    -   Configuration for environment variables (API keys, database connection strings, etc.).\n\n\n"}}
